Nature Reviews Psychology
Review article
By contrast, stimulant use is frequently initiated in social contexts 
with positive reinforcement motives (an increase in the probability 
of a response produced by the presentation of a drug, or reward)25, 
and stimulants are used to enhance more than to relieve depression 
or other negative states26. In 2023, opioid overdoses continued to 
pose a severe public health threat, contributing to approximately 
81,083 opioid-related deaths out of an estimated 107,543 total drug 
overdose deaths27. Hopes that deaths would decline as life returned 
to normal after the COVID-19 pandemic faded owing to persistently 
high fatality rates, particularly driven by synthetic opioids such as 
fentanyl27. Despite these alarming statistics, the neurobehavioural 
features of opioid use disorder continue to be understudied relative 
to other drugs.
In this Review, we examine the idiosyncratic role of impulsivity in 
opioid use disorder, with a particular focus on negative affectivity and 
negative reinforcement processes. First, we describe the dimensions 
of impulsivity, including the role of emotion and its interplay with 
stability and change in impulsive behaviour and cognition. Next, we 
overview the literature about emotion-neutral and emotion-elicited 
trait and state impulsivity in opioid use disorder and consider nega-
tive affectivity and negative reinforcement as potential mediators of 
the link between impulsivity and opioid addiction at all three stages 
of the addiction cycle. We then identify four mechanisms (negative 
urgency, psychopathy, hyperkatifeia, and pain and hyperalgesia) that 
reflect the complex interactions between the impulsivity dimensions 
and the distinct stages of the opioid addiction cycle: opioid use for pain 
relief or emotional escape as the entry point, and the salient negative 
emotional states that trigger cravings and compulsive drug use. Finally, 
we discuss the importance of the withdrawal/negative affect stage and 
related mechanisms in opioid addiction, and conclude with directions 
for future research that target negative reinforcement mechanisms to 
boost clinical treatment.
Our characterization of impulsivity in opioid use disorder is 
derived largely from a seminal model of addiction (known as the ‘dark 
side of addiction’ model28,29), which proposes that addiction develops 
from positive reinforcement mechanisms (linked to brain reward 
systems and drug-induced euphoria) in the early stages of the cycle, 
to negative reinforcement mechanisms (linked to brain stress systems 
and ‘antireward’ systems that limit reward processes and drive negative 
emotional states) in the later stages.
Dimensions of impulsivity
Meta-analyses of studies on the latent structure of impulsivity reveal 
that impulsivity has a multifactorial structure, thereby empirically 
verifying its multifaceted nature30,31. Alternatively, a more parsimonious 
model proposes that a two-factor structure of impulsivity maps more 
closely onto substance use disorders32: one factor indexes impulse to 
approach drugs and the other factor indexes decreased inhibitory 
control over this approach behaviour. For the purposes of this Review, 
we categorize impulsivity based on the role of emotion in impulsive 
behaviour33,34 (emotion-elicited versus emotion-neutral impulsivity) 
and stability and change (state versus trait impulsivity) (Table 1).
Emotional dimension
A longstanding framework in cognitive neuroscience distinguishes 
between cognition or behaviour under emotion-eliciting (‘hot’) con-
texts versus contexts or task features that ostensibly do not elicit 
emotion (‘cool’)35. According to the initial sources of this framework, 
the ‘hot’ system involves quick reactions to intense emotionally 
Introduction
Impulsivity, a rapid, unplanned reaction without regard to potential 
negative consequences1, is implicated in the development and main-
tenance of all addictive behaviours and disorders. It is considered 
an antecedent risk factor for substance use initiation and transition 
into compulsive use2–5, a consequence of chronic drug use3 and an 
endophenotype of addiction3,5–8. Impulsivity is a complex and multi-
faceted construct characterized by multiple personality, psychiatric 
and neurocognitive factors that are only weakly correlated9–13. This 
multifaceted structure involves a dimension related to emotional 
aspects of impulsive behaviour (emotion-elicited or ‘hot’ impulsivity 
versus emotion-neutral or ‘cool’ impulsivity) and a dimension related 
to stability and change of impulsive behaviour (relatively stable dispo-
sitional trait impulsivity versus relatively fluctuating state impulsivity). 
These dimensions interact in complex ways with different forms of 
psychopathology. For example, there are substance-specific varia-
tions in impulsivity presentation across substance use disorders and 
at different stages of the addiction cycle8,14.
A prevailing model of substance use disorders conceptualizes the 
development of addiction as a three-stage process of neurotransmitter 
and stress-response neuroadaptations that operate at two different 
timescales15. The first timescale is an episodic cycle of acute binge and 
intoxication with co-occurring euphoria (‘binge/intoxication’ stage), 
followed by the acute metabolic clearance of the drug that triggers 
an aversive psychological and somatic state (‘withdrawal/negative 
affect’ stage), and subsequent preoccupation and anticipation with 
co-occurring strong and urgent desire to use the drug or craving 
(‘preoccupation/anticipation’ stage). The second timescale is the rep-
etition of the initially episodic cycle over time, which progressively 
alters neurotransmitter circuitry and stress responses and disrupts 
brain reward, stress and executive function systems16.
A neuroscience-informed clinical framework for addictions 
(the Addictions Neuroclinical Assessment17) based on research domain 
criteria18 loosely maps these three stages onto experimentally detect-
able alterations in three corresponding neurofunctional domains. The 
first neurofunctional domain, incentive salience of drug-associated 
cues (including rituals), is associated with phasic dopaminergic 
activation in the basal ganglia during the binge/intoxication stage. 
The second domain, negative emotionality, is associated with the 
engagement of brain stress systems that drive the withdrawal/negative 
affect stage. The third domain, executive function, is associated with 
reduced prefrontal cortex-mediated top-down impulse control during 
the preoccupation/anticipation stage. This neuroscience-informed 
framework has been assumed to apply to essentially all substance use 
disorders19, but its application to opioid use disorder is still not well 
understood (with some exceptions20).
Negative reinforcement (an increase in the probability of a 
response produced by the removal of an aversive stimulus or event) 
is characteristic of all addictive drugs, especially in advanced stages 
of addiction that feature physiological tolerance and psychological 
dependence in which an individual uses the substance to feel better 
(temporarily). However, negatively reinforced use of opioids can begin 
much earlier in the pathophysiological development of addiction 
compared with other drugs because opioids are frequently diverted 
and self-administered to terminate or reduce physical pain14,21,22, and 
because the physiological opioid withdrawal state is profoundly aver-
sive compared with that of other substances. Indeed, most Americans 
who reported the use of diverted opioid medication were motivated 
primarily by pain relief, not by positive affect or to get ‘high’23,24. 
