arousing stimuli that trigger pleasure, pain and fear, which are medi-
ated by phylogenetically older brain structures such as the basal ganglia 
and the amygdala36. The ‘cool’ system is cognitive, controlled and slower 
to activate than the ‘hot’ system, has a critical role in self-control and 
future-orientated decisions, and is mediated by the prefrontal cortex. 
The ‘hot–cool’ framework of cognitive function has been applied pri-
marily to executive functions to distinguish between ‘motivational 
control’ (hot) and ‘cognitive control’ (cool)37.
Impulsivity can similarly be fractionated into emotion-elicited 
and emotion-neutral dimensions based on the influence of emotion 
on impulsive behaviour34,38. Examples of emotion-elicited impulsive 
behaviour are urgency (acting impulsively in the face of strong posi-
tive or negative emotions) or sensation seeking (seeking out novel and 
exciting experiences). On neurobehavioural tasks, emotion-elicited 
impulsivity is closely linked to and operationalized by affective and 
motivational processes such as emotion regulation, prospects of 
reward and punishment, and the ability to tolerate emotional distress or 
delay gratification. On self-report measures, ‘hot’ impulsivity is indexed 
through questions that assess the frequency and intensity of positive 
and negative urgency and of sensation-seeking behaviour in question-
naires such as the Urgency–Premeditation–Perseverance–Sensation 
Seeking–Positive Urgency (UPPS-P) impulsive behaviour scale39 .
By contrast, emotion-neutral impulsivity refers to more decontex-
tualized cognitive processes involving attention, response inhibition 
and working memory. On neurobehavioural tasks, emotion-neutral 
impulsive behaviour is identified through erroneous responses 
to non-target stimuli or incomplete processing of target stimuli. 
On self-report questionnaires such as the Barratt Impulsiveness Scale40, 
‘cool’ impulsivity is indexed by questions assessing the ability to focus 
on current tasks, acting at the spur of the moment, or planning and 
thinking deliberately.
Neuroimaging studies support the separability of emotion-elicited 
and emotion-neutral impulsivity dimensions by showing that they are 
ostensibly mediated by different prefrontal cortex areas33,35,37,41. How-
ever, some studies reveal that whereas both dimensions are mediated 
by similar prefrontal regions and the insula, emotion-eliciting tasks 
also recruit salience and emotional processing regions42,43, suggesting 
that there might be both common and unique processes across ‘hot’ 
and ‘cool’ impulsivity37.
Stability and change dimension
Similar to other constructs such as anxiety44 and anger45, impulsivity 
can manifest as a relatively stable pre-existing individual personality 
characteristic that causes and explains consistent behavioural patterns 
(trait)46 or as a more transient characteristic that influences behaviour 
over a relatively short time frame47 (states). Generally, impulsivity as a 
trait is related to between-person variability and impulsivity as a state 
to within-person variability47.
Impulsivity is one of the most ubiquitous personality traits and can 
be found in one form or another in all major theories of personality48–52. 
Dimensional theories of psychopathology consider personality traits 
subclinical or prodromal forms of mental disorders53, with impul-
sivity being considered one of the most fundamental trans-disease 
features54,55. Moreover, elevated trait impulsivity has long been con-
sidered a pre-existing vulnerability factor for the development and 
maintenance of substance-related and addictive disorders3,56 (Box 1). 
Impulsivity is also a prime transdiagnostic symptom for a wide range of 
psychiatric disorders that are commonly comorbid with substance use 
