disorders57, most prominently externalizing disorders, such as attention 
deficit hyperactivity disorder, disruptive behaviour disorders (oppo-
sitional defiant disorder or conduct disorder), antisocial personality 
disorder, borderline personality disorder and bipolar disorder.
Self-report questionnaires typically index trait impulsivity based 
on models that differ in the extent to which they engage emotion-
elicited versus emotion-neutral mechanisms (Box 2). Emotion-elicited 
impulsive acts are typically framed as driven by current positive or 
negative mood, such as negative urgency, the tendency to act without 
thinking when one is upset, or positive urgency, the tendency to act 
without thinking when one is excited. Other conceptualizations of trait 
impulsivity58 posit a more central role of time perception and cognitive 
effort and a minimal role of emotion. For example, lack of premedita-
tion (the ability to plan and think ahead) and lack of perseverance 
(persistence in pursuing goals or ability to stay focused on a task) are 
used to index ‘cool’ trait impulsivity in some scales39.
In contrast with trait impulsivity as an enduring individual differ-
ence, state impulsivity is a more transient vulnerability to rash action 
that might occur, for example, when a person is aroused or fatigued. 
These states can result in incomplete evaluation of stimuli and pro-
mote erroneous rapid responses and snap decisions to reward and 
punishment contingencies. State impulsivity involves two broad neuro­
behavioural constructs that are typically captured using neurocog-
nitive performance tasks12,13. The first construct is emotion-neutral 
neurocognitive impulsivity manifested as rapid, premature responses 
involving either the cancellation of an ongoing response or the inhi-
bition of inappropriate actions, and acting without properly assess-
ing context (‘impulsive action’30 or ‘rapid-response impulsivity’12). 
Box 1 | Impulsivity in addiction to different classes of drugs
 
Emotion-elicited and emotion-neutral impulsivity are differentially 
implicated in distinct substance use disorders.
Nicotine use disorder
There are strong links between impulsivity traits and the onset 
and persistence of nicotine use disorder303. The strongest 
predictors of smoking status and nicotine use disorder severity 
among adults were positive urgency and premeditation304 
(r = 0.24 and r = 0.20, respectively), whereas sensation seeking was 
more strongly associated with nicotine use among adolescents 
(r = 0.20)305,306. This contention is further supported by prospective 
studies in which trait-based sensation seeking and risk taking 
were particularly predictive of tobacco use initiation among 
youths307. These findings underscore that positively reinforced 
emotion-elicited trait impulsivity might have a distinct role on the 
initial stages of nicotine use disorder and on the progression of 
nicotine use. Chronic exposure to nicotine was also associated 
with emotion-elicited state impulsivity; for example, chronic 
nicotine users focused predominantly on immediate rewards at 
the expense of larger delayed rewards308. By contrast, chronic 
nicotine users showed a relatively intact response inhibition, 
indicating that nicotine use disorder does not seem to be related 
to emotion-neutral state impulsivity when compared to other 
substance use disorders122,134.
Alcohol use disorder
Alcohol use disorder was associated with a mix of emotion-elicited 
and emotion-neutral impulsivity traits, with the strongest relationship 
observed with negative urgency and lack of premeditation309 (r = 0.38 
and r = 0.37, respectively). By contrast, emotion-elicited impulsivity 
traits (particularly negative and positive urgency) have been 
linked to aversive consequences associated with alcohol use309,310. 
Regarding state impulsivity, alcohol use disorder was associated 
with a blend of deficits in both emotion-elicited and emotion-neutral 
neurocognitive dimensions of impulsivity, as evidenced by moderate 
response inhibition deficits (g = 0.4–0.5)134,311, higher rates of delay 
discounting312–314 and compromised decision-making315–318. Critically, 
deficits in emotion-elicited state impulsivity remained stable 
even during extended periods of abstinence319, which highlights 
their persistent and enduring presence within the alcohol use 
disorder cycle.
Cannabis use disorder
Cannabis use was weakly associated with various emotion-elicited 
and emotion-neutral impulsivity traits, such as positive urgency 
(r = 0.23), sensation seeking (r = 0.22) and lack of premeditation 
(r = 0.13)320. However, these traits were connected to the negative 
consequences of cannabis use rather than cannabis use per se320. 
This finding suggests that impulsivity traits might help identify 
the likelihood of suffering the negative effects from cannabis use, 
rather than the likelihood of becoming addicted to cannabis. 
Similar to nicotine use disorder, meta-analytic studies do not 
support increased emotion-neutral state impulsivity among chronic 
cannabis users122,134,321. By contrast, small to moderate deficits in 
decision-making and delay discounting (r = 0.08)322 were related 
to cannabis use disorder, indicating that emotion-elicited state 
impulsivity might be involved in the cannabis addiction cycle322,323. 
Nonetheless, impairments in emotion-elicited state impulsivity 
seem to be less pronounced in cannabis use disorders than in other 
substance use disorders323,324.
Stimulant use disorder
Stimulant use disorder is associated with high trait impulsivity and 
marked impairments in both emotion-elicited and emotion-neutral 
state impulsivity, such as negative urgency325,326, positive urgency326, 
sensation seeking95,327,328, lack of premeditation326 and motor 
impulsivity95,110. Stimulants (for example, cocaine, amphetamines 
or methamphetamines) have a more powerful influence on 
impulsive action than many other drug classes (for example, 
cannabis, nicotine or opioids), with more pronounced effects on 
emotion-neutral state impulsivity122,329. Cocaine use disorder and 
methamphetamine use disorder were associated with impairments 
in emotion-neutral state impulsivity with moderate to large effect 
sizes (g = 0.4–0.7), suggesting compromised response inhibition in 
stimulant use disorder134. In addition, stimulant use disorder was 
associated with disadvantageous decision-making330,331 and steep 
delay discounting95,332, underscoring the additional involvement of 
emotion-elicited state impulsivity in this disorder.
