These behaviours are typically presented in tasks or contexts in which 
there are no emotionally evocative stimuli. The second construct is 
emotion-elicited neurocognitive impulsivity, present, for example, 
when evocative task stimuli (such as vivid images) degrade executive 
brain function to increase errors in signal detection or memory tasks59, 
when application of emotionally evocative music induces a prefer-
ence for smaller immediate rewards over larger delayed rewards60 or 
when other abilities to make decisions in line with long-term goals are 
compromised (‘impulsive choice’13 or ‘decisional impulsivity’61).
Self-control over behaviour might be differentially instantiated 
in the brain at distinct timescales through different neuroanatomical 
areas62. Immediate reward tasks recruited antero-ventral striatum63–65, 
and therefore this area might be a potential common neurocircuit driver 
of impulsive choice and decisional impulsivity. By contrast, motor 
impulsive action was linked to the right anterior insula66 and the dorsal 
anterior cingulate cortex67, whereas self-controlled choices in decision-
making paradigms selectively recruited medial-orbitofrontal68 and 
dorsolateral cortices69,70.
Although there are some self-report metrics of state impulsivity 
(typically administered via ecological momentary assessment71,72), 
the vast majority of state impulsivity measures are task-based neuro­
behavioural paradigms of impulsive choice and/or impulsive action73. 
State-based metrics of impulsivity are more precisely captured by 
computational models that deconstruct neurobehavioural perfor-
mance into underlying latent processes to understand its specific 
mechanisms74,75. These computational approaches also improve the 
sensitivity to between-subject effects relative to standard neuro­
behavioural performance indices76–78. For example, a study revealed 
that the computational decision-making parameters of risk tolerance 
and ambiguity tolerance are more variable across time than delay 
discounting (the tendency to value rewards less when they are delayed 
in time)79. This finding suggests that risk and ambiguity tolerance 
might more closely reflect an individual’s current state, whereas delay 
discounting might be more stable (as a trait).
Questionnaire assessments of impulsivity have generally 
been found to be more reliable than task-based neurobehavioural 
Box 2 | Measurement of impulsivity
 
The arguments in our Review are informed by dual-systems models of 
cognition and personality that use diverse measures of the facets 
of impulsivity, which continue to evolve.
Dual-systems models
One of the earliest dual-systems models of cognition dates to the 
1960s, with the characterization of a ‘hot’ emotional system and a 
‘cool’ cognitive system involved in self-control36. The ‘hot’ and ‘cool’ 
systems are closely interconnected and engaged in reciprocal 
relationship: as one becomes more active, the other becomes 
less active36. There is a maturational imbalance between the two 
systems, with the ‘hot’ system developing early, whereas the ‘cool’ 
system does not fully mature until the early twenties333. Other 
similar dual-systems theories propose two main types of cognitive 
processes: a ‘hot’ system 1, which is fast, impulsive and automatic; 
and a ‘cool’ system 2, which is slow, reflective and effortful334.
‘Hot’ trait impulsivity measures
Derived from the five-factor model of personality, the UPPS-P88,281 
proposes that there are five trait impulsivity dimensions, which reflect 
individual differences in lack of premeditation, lack of perseverance, 
negative and/or positive urgency, and sensation seeking. The first 
two dimensions are emotion neutral, and the last three emotion 
dependent89. This model is used to identify the relative importance of 
emotional versus non-emotional ingredients of impulsivity in diverse 
behaviours178.
‘Cool’ trait impulsivity measures
The Barratt Impulsiveness Scale (BIS-11) was developed to relate 
impulsiveness and anxiety to laboratory tasks of learning and 
psychomotor function40,58,335 and is arguably the most commonly 
administered trait impulsivity measure336. This model conceptualizes 
impulsivity as a multidimensional trait that reflects a broad 
predisposition towards impulsive behaviour, which is orthogonal 
to anxiety58. Factor analyses of the BIS-11 reveal motor, attentional 
and nonplanning subtypes40. Notably, the item content of the BIS-11 
features behaviours that are not explicitly driven by pronounced 
positive or negative mood in the wording of questions.
State impulsivity measures
Neurobehavioural tasks of state impulsivity are complex tasks 
that involve many motivational, learning and choice processes to 
capture important aspects of real-life functioning337. Thus, impaired 
performance on such tasks could have many different causes that 
reflect distinct underlying mechanisms, such as sensitivity to reward, 
sensitivity to loss, risk tolerance or ambiguity tolerance, which are not 
well captured by traditional neurobehavioural performance indices. 
For example, computational modelling of decision-making reveals 
that this ‘hot’ neurocognitive function comprises both ‘hot’ and ‘cool’ 
underlying processes, such as reward sensitivity and loss aversion 
(emotion elicited) versus learning or memory (emotion neutral).
The dual-process theory has been applied to computational 
modelling of decision-making that involves uncertainty and learning 
by trial and error. These studies reveal that system 1 and system 
2 interact in a competitive, rather than sequential manner, and 
that accumulating experience leads to adjusting the strategies to 
complete the task and speeds the decision-making process, in which 
the initially slow and effortful ‘cool’ decision-making is replaced by 
faster and automatic ‘hot’ decision-making processes338.
Measurement stability
Some ‘hot’ state impulsivity constructs (such as delay discounting) 
have both trait and state properties47,79,339. Critically, state measures 
of impulsivity have a different purpose than trait measures340. 
Indeed, whereas high reliability is desirable when measuring trait-like 
characteristics, reliability is neither necessary nor sufficient to 
capture change over time or state-like characteristics340. Rather than 
measuring individual differences (which requires high reliability), 
some state measures are designed to measure change over time 
(for example, to assess the effects of treatment or abstinence). 
Thus, some state measures might be less consistent with repeated 
administration than trait measures.
