assessments80,81. This difference has been attributed to questionnaires 
generally querying behaviours over longer timescales or asking about 
daily behavioural propensities. By contrast, laboratory cognitive per-
formance metrics might depend on several transient factors, such as 
fatigue82, presence of distractions in the environment83 or internal 
distractions such as intrusive rumination or pain84. Similarly, some rein-
forcers might elicit more impulsivity than others and some outcomes 
are discounted more steeply than others. For example, people tend to 
discount delayed non-monetary outcomes such as drugs of abuse more 
steeply than monetary outcomes85. However, questionnaires might be 
less reliable86,87 if the trait is expressed in contextualized ways across 
different situations88,89. Repeated administration of neurobehavioural 
tasks along with self-report measures have shown that self-report 
measures could also be state-like and change within an individual. 
For example, a study that analysed the reliability and validity of an 
ecological momentary assessment adaptation of the UPPS impulsive 
behaviour scale found that self-report impulsive states were broadly 
consistent with the five-factor model of impulsive traits71.
Despite these considerations and the fact that trait and state 
impulsivity are generally high in clinical populations, they are typically 
not well correlated within subject5,31,90. Laboratory metrics of ‘hot’ and 
‘cool’ neurocognitive state impulsivity might have less naturalistic 
relevance and show fewer effects on metacognition than self-reported 
questionnaires that capture trait impulsivity91. These distinctions 
underscore the independent contributions of state and trait impul-
sivity to the risk of substance use disorders5,8 and the diagnostic and 
prognostic utility of their concurrent assessment.
Impulsivity in opioid use disorder
The specific genetic variance estimates (the extent of variability attrib-
uted to genetic factors unique to a specific drug category, rather than 
those shared across various drugs) of opioid use disorder (0.38) versus 
other substance use disorders (ranging from 0.00 to 0.11)92–94, com-
bined with neurobiological and neurocognitive differences between 
different types of addiction76,95–101, suggest that impulsivity dimen-
sions are not uniformly involved in addictions to various classes of 
drugs and that some of these dimensions might be specific to opioid 
use disorder. In this section, we overview studies of these impulsivity 
dimensions in opioid users and compare the findings with those of 
other substance users.
Trait impulsivity
A limited number of studies have investigated ‘hot’ and ‘cool’ trait-based 
impulsivity dimensions in opioid users by comparing their self-reports 
with those of control participants or other groups of substance users.
Emotion-neutral trait impulsivity. Most of the self-report studies show 
increased trait impulsivity in opioid users compared with control indi-
viduals with no history of chronic substance use102–105 (Table 2). However, 
relative to other types of substance use disorders, research suggests that 
opioid use disorder is less strongly associated with emotion-neutral trait 
impulsivity, such as attentional impulsivity (the tendency to be easily 
distracted and have difficulty maintaining focus on a task) and motor 
impulsivity95,106–108 (the tendency to act rashly without forethought, 
typically resulting in unpremeditated actions)106–110. Moreover, only 
specific facets of emotion-neutral trait impulsivity95,111–113 were impli-
cated in opioid use disorder. For example, in a review of studies that 
linked baseline trait impulsivity to treatment outcome, a measure of 
general ‘cool’ trait impulsivity (BIS) predicted poor treatment outcomes 
in alcohol use disorder and cocaine use disorder treatments, but not in 
opioid use disorder treatment114. In another study, lack of premedita-
tion uniquely predicted opioid misuse in patients with chronic pain, 
and the effect of this trait on misuse was higher than those of other 
emotion-elicited impulsivity constructs identified in previous studies113. 
Lack of premeditation was also associated with poor prognosis in opioid 
use treatment and difficulties in abstaining from opioids despite initial 
intentions115. Additional research has identified lack of premeditation 
as a key factor influencing the gap between intended abstinence from 
opioids and opioid use within the past 30 days116.
Although lack of premeditation is generally considered part of 
the ‘cool’ impulsivity domain, it might align more closely with ‘hot’ 
impulsivity if chronic failure to plan reflects a lifestyle driven by imme-
diate reactions to environmental circumstances and stressors rather 
than future-orientated thinking. This pattern suggests a broader life-
time tendency towards delay discounting, extending beyond specific 
reward scenarios. However, the reviewed findings indicated a nuanced 
relationship in which specific emotion-neutral impulsivity constructs 
might contribute to opioid-related behaviours, such as difficulties in 
following treatment plans and challenges in maintaining abstinence 
from opioid use.
Emotion-elicited trait impulsivity. Opioid use disorder is closely 
linked to personality traits reflecting elevated negative affectivity, 
such as trait anxiety, anxiety sensitivity, depression and anger95,117. 
Similarly, trait impulsivity in opioid use disorders might be mediated 
by negative affectivity domains, such as depression111 and anxiety102. 
Thus, emotion-elicited trait impulsivity might play a more relevant role 
in the opioid addiction cycle than emotion-neutral trait impulsivity.
The tendency to act impulsively under negative emotional states 
(negative urgency) is especially pronounced as a negative reinforce-
ment mechanism for pain relief. This tendency has also been involved 
in theoretical models of substance use in the context of pain-related 
negative affect118. In contrast with the role of ‘cool’ trait impulsivity 
on adherence to treatment and abstinence, ‘hot’ trait impulsivity as 
manifested by negative urgency is evident during stages of intensified 
negative emotions such as withdrawal and craving113. For example, 
elevated negative urgency was associated with increased opioid crav-
ings over the past 3 months and last-month illicit stimulant use in a 
study conducted in a sample of opioid users119. This finding indicates 
that negative urgency induced by withdrawal amid lack of access to 
opioids might be a critical factor in understanding the later stages of 
the opioid addiction cycle.
Other trait-based emotion-driven impulsivity constructs that 
have been identified as relevant factors underlying opioid use disorder 
are sensation seeking and positive urgency. Sensation seeking was 
a predictor of poor outcomes of opioid use disorder treatment and 
difficulties in maintaining abstinence115,116. Positive urgency was associ-
ated with drug-cue-induced craving and increased delay discounting120 
(Table 3). Combined, these findings suggest that emotion-elicited trait 
­impulsivity is a prominent feature of opioid use disorder.
State impulsivity
Emotion-neutral state impulsivity assessed through response disin-
hibition or impulsive action paradigms seems to be more strongly 
associated with other substance use disorders than with opioid use 
disorder100,101,121,122. Conversely, emotion-elicited state impulsivity 
examined through decision-making and delay discounting tasks was 
identified as a prominent feature of the opioid addiction cycle95,123,124.
Nature Reviews Psychology
Review article
Emotion-neutral state impulsivity. Findings on the role of emotion-
neutral state impulsivity in opioid use disorder are highly incon-
sistent (Table 4). Some of the early studies in the field reported 
impaired response inhibition in opioid users125–128, whereas other 
studies found no differences in performance between these users 
and control participants97,100,121,128–132. Some studies have even 
found better response inhibition in opioid users than in healthy 
control individuals120,133. These conflicting findings might be due to the 
diverse array of samples included in studies, including active heroin 
users129,132, patients enrolled in maintenance treatment120,125,126 or opioid 
users in early (<12 months)101,121,127,128,131 versus protracted abstinence 
(>12 months)128,130. This variability makes it difficult to draw consistent 
conclusions about the role of emotion-neutral neurocognitive impul-
sivity at different stages of opioid addiction. However, the limited 
number of studies conducted with mono-dependent opioid users 
report overall intact response inhibition in this population95,120,128,131. 
Relatedly, a meta-analysis of meta-analyses of impulsivity in substance 
use disorders122 indicated that increased scores on ‘cool’ state impul-
sivity indices (such as ‘no-go’ commission errors) were more consist-
ently linked to alcohol and stimulant use disorders than to opioid and 
