cannabis use disorders. Similarly, machine-learning studies reported 
that opioid use disorder was uniquely predicted by relatively intact 
response inhibition95. Combined, these findings have led to the conclu-
sion that emotion-neutral state impulsivity is not a key discriminating 
feature of opioid use disorder134.
The substantial variation in the tasks used to capture emotion-
neutral state impulsivity represents a challenge in interpreting these 
findings. Many studies have utilized go/no-go and stop signal tasks 
as equivalent measures of response inhibition. However, these par-
adigms tap into different cognitive processes (such as automatic 
bottom-up inhibition in go/no-go tasks versus controlled top-down 
inhibition in stop signal tasks135) that are governed by separate neural 
pathways136,137, and distinct underlying mechanisms might be differen-
tially engaged at distinct stages of the addiction cycle. For example, 
although opioid users might retain effective top-down inhibition (as 
indexed by an increased ability to cancel an already initiated motor 
response), their automatic inhibition (typically measured by tasks 
engaging the ability to inhibit a prepotent motor reaction) seems to be 
compromised128. This result suggests a nuanced cognitive landscape 
in which opioid use disorder influences some, but not all, aspects of 
inhibitory control.
The engagement of emotional processes can also influence ‘cool’ 
inhibitory control in opioid users, which highlights the complex inter-
play between emotional triggers and cognitive control mechanisms. 
When negative emotional stimuli or drug-related cues were integrated 
into response inhibition tasks, opioid users exhibited substantial chal-
lenges in their inhibitory capacities138. In a direct comparison between 
persons with diverse primary substance use disorder, emotional face 
targets in an emotion–face go/no-go behavioural task elicited higher 
hit rates than neutral face targets in all groups. By contrast, fearful faces 
targets were associated with reduced hit rates only among participants 
with opioid use disorder, suggesting an exaggerated attention to fear 
stimuli in this group96. In another study, stimuli related to negative 
emotions and opioids led to more frequent commission errors and 
delayed reaction times compared with stimuli related to neutral or 
positive emotions138. Moreover, automatic positive emotional process-
ing enhanced response inhibition among heroin abstainers relative 
to a control group, especially under subliminal emotional priming133, 
suggesting that emotional cues can substantially alter the inhibitory 
control abilities of people recovering from opioid addiction.
Emotion-driven state impulsivity. Research on emotion-driven state 
impulsivity in people with opioid use disorder has provided more 
consistent findings, which reveal robust impairments in diverse forms 
of decision-making14,95,121,125,128,139–148 and delay discounting120,128,139,149–155 
(Table 5). Similarly, machine-learning findings identified disadvanta-
geous decision-making as one of the strongest unique predictors 
of opioid use disorder95, and meta-analytic studies indicated that 
decision-making was among the most severely and consistently 
impaired neurocognitive functions in opioid use disorder123,124. Still, 
some studies characterized opioid users as having a relatively intact 
performance on decision-making and delay discounting tasks com-
pared with other groups of substance-dependent individuals100,144,150,156, 
whereas other studies reported no differences between opioid use and 
other substance use disorders on these measures76,101,107,157.
The tasks that have been used to examine emotion-elicited state 
impulsivity in opioid use disorder target distinct latent processes, 
each governed by unique neural circuits78,158 that are linked to distinct 
stages of the opioid addiction cycle. For example, decision-making 
under ambiguity, typically measured by tasks involving deci-
sions under unknown probabilities of outcomes (such as the Iowa 
Gambling Task) recruits the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex, the 
subcallosal anterior cingulate cortex and the parietal cortex158. By 
contrast, decision-making under risk, assessed through tasks involv-
ing known probabilities of rewards and losses (such as the Cambridge 
Gambling Task), engages the orbitofrontal cortex, the rostral ante-
rior cingulate cortex and the parietal cortex158. Delay discounting 
is associated with activations in the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex, 
orbitofrontal cortex, medial prefrontal cortex, posterior parietal 
cortex and ventral striatum159.
Relatedly, a study conducted in a real-world clinical context found 
that a computational marker of decision-making characterized by 
increased ambiguity tolerance independently predicted imminent 
opioid use during methadone maintenance treatment, even after con-
trolling for other well-established clinical predictors, such as craving77. 
This finding underscores the role of ambiguity tolerance as a situational 
