(state) vulnerability marker, potentially indicating imminent risk of 
opioid use. By contrast, the computational marker of risk tolerance 
was unrelated to opioid use during treatment77. Patients with opioid use 
disorder were more tolerant of known risks than control participants, 
suggesting that the computational marker of risk tolerance might be 
a trait-based vulnerability factor (potentially predicting relapses in 
the long term).
Critically, impairments in emotion-elicited state impulsivity in 
opioid users persist well into the protracted abstinence stage of the opi-
oid addiction cycle and might last years after discontinuation of opioid 
use124,128, which might amplify or prolong vulnerability to relapse160. 
Such persistent effects on decision-making and delay discounting were 
further supported by neuroimaging studies identifying long-lasting 
neuroadaptations in prefrontal regions and chronic impairments in 
dopamine transmission in long-term abstinent opioid users (for a 
review, see ref. 124.). In addition, emotion-elicited state impulsivity 
constructs have been identified as robust predictors of relapse, human 
immunodeficiency virus risk behaviours and other negative treatment 
outcomes in opioid users34,161,162, further emphasizing their critical role 
in the later stages of the opioid addiction cycle.
In sum, although impulsivity is a transdiagnostic marker across the 
addiction spectrum, emerging evidence reveals that certain types of 
impulsivity might play a less direct and less central role in opioid use 
disorder than in other types of substance use disorders. Specifically, 
findings emphasize that emotion-driven trait and state impulsivities 
are more strongly implicated in the later stages of opioid use disorder, 
whereas emotion-neutral trait and state impulsivity are less relevant, 
except in cases in which ‘cool’ impulsivity tasks also engaged emotional 
processes. These findings highlight the emotional nexus of impulsivity 
in opioid use disorder and suggest that impulsivity might be driven 
by the quest for either pain relief or the avoidance of the negative 
emotional states that characterize the withdrawal and craving stages 
of opioid use disorder. Indeed, the severe symptoms of opioid with-
drawal are a powerful reinforcer for continued use22 that makes the 
withdrawal/negative affect stage particularly pronounced. In the next 
section, we describe negative affectivity and negative reinforcement 
mechanisms as the driving forces of impulsivity across all stages of the 
opioid addiction cycle21 (Fig. 1).
Mechanisms driving impulsivity
There are at least four (nonexclusive) mechanisms that might play a 
role in explaining the variety of impulsivity-related impairments in 
opioid addiction. Two of these mechanisms (negative urgency and 
psychopathy) pertain to individual differences in impulsive personality 
traits. The other two mechanisms are state-like and reflect the cumu-
lative impact of long-term opioid exposure and repeated episodes 
of withdrawal, which result in progressive worsening of the negative 
emotional symptoms of withdrawal (hyperkatifeia) and sensitization 
to the physical symptoms of withdrawal via increased sensitivity to 
pain (hyperalgesia). These four mechanisms are differentially related 
to the ‘hot’ and ‘cool’ dimensions of impulsivity in opioid users. The key 
feature of these mechanisms is negative affectivity, which might medi-
ate the relationship between impulsivity and all stages of opioid addic-
tion. In this section, we build on these associations to provide a more 
