Fig. 1 | Changes in the opioid addiction cycle over time. a, A single drug use 
event induces a sequence of euphoria characterized by increases in dopamine 
and other neurotransmitters (binge/intoxication stage, blue), followed by an 
aversive acute withdrawal state characterized by reduced dopamine levels and 
increased initiation of stress responses (withdrawal/negative affect stage, red), 
followed by a preoccupation stage in which the individual is preoccupied with 
and anticipating the next drug use event (preoccupation/anticipation stage, 
yellow). b, Neuroadaptations occur with repeated intoxication cycles, which 
initially feature pronounced euphoria, but modest withdrawal and minimal 
preoccupation. Repeated cycles lead to pronounced withdrawal responses that 
in turn trigger increased preoccupation with the next drug-taking event and 
eventually compulsive or uncontrolled opioid use. c, An allostasis framework 
illustrates how affect during the three stages of the cycle changes across the 
development of addiction. Neuroadaptations within the addiction cycle drive 
allostasis over time, wherein the individual’s default mood state or homeostatic 
‘set-point’ progressively lowers during the descent from recreational drug use 
to compulsive or uncontrolled use. Part c is adapted from ref. 302, Springer 
Nature Limited.
