anxiety (and specifically the neuroendocrine sequelae of these intense 
mood states) can degrade the executive brain functions required for 
self-control on immediate timescales or for optimal decision-making 
on longer timescales. In addition, negative urgency might impair 
self-control in emotional contexts, leading to failures in response 
inhibition165. Negative urgency is thought to have a bidirectional func-
tion in the development and maintenance of substance use disorders, 
acting both as a predisposing risk factor166,167 and as a consequence of 
chronic drug use168. Negative urgency has been suggested as a diag-
nostic marker of addiction, as it integrates the impulsive and compul-
sive stages of the addiction cycle via neurocircuitries engaged in the 
affective dysregulation associated with the progression of drug use168.
In addition to being a unique predictor of opioid use disorder95 
and a key mechanism underlying opioid addiction169, accumulating 
evidence reveals that negative urgency is linked to negative treatment 
outcomes in opioid users (such as cravings and illicit substance use dur-
ing treatment119) and current and future opioid misuse and symptoms 
of opioid use disorder in patients with chronic pain170. For example, pain 
patients scoring high in negative urgency might respond to intense 
bouts of pain by seeking extra (diverted) opioids for immediate relief 
despite medical risk, such as overdose. Addicted patients scoring high 
in negative urgency might respond to the emergent unpleasant feelings 
amid therapeutic discussions or to setbacks by abandoning sobriety 
goals to immediately but temporarily escape feelings of sadness or 
hopelessness.
In persons with high levels of negative urgency, intense negative 
affect might stoke impulsivity by interfering with brain mechanisms 
that would otherwise (in the absence of emotional duress) create and 
reference mental representations of self and future consequences. 
In this context, negative urgency leads to disadvantageous and sub-
optimal decisions such as increased focus on immediate rewards 
at the expense of longer-term considerations. A prevailing model 
of emotional and physical acute stress effects on cognition posits 
that increased catecholamine levels circulating in the prefrontal 
cortex (as a component of the stress response) activate lower affinity 
receptors in the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex, and cause intracel-
lular second messenger activity that degrades the signal-to-noise 
ratio of dorsolateral prefrontal cortex neurons and their ability to 
‘top-down regulate’ other brain circuitry171. This is thought to be a 
mechanism of stress-induced ‘tunnelling’ of attentional focus by 
negative arousal172 and other cognitive effects not conducive to reflec-
tion, such as proneness to more simplistic methods of forming asso-
ciations between one’s choices and experienced rewards in stochastic 
learning tasks173–177.
As an emotion-elicited trait, negative urgency has a critical role 
in understanding the transitions through the different stages of the 
opioid addiction cycle. Opioid users with high levels of trait negative 
urgency might prioritize short-term gains over the potential long-term 
benefits of their choices when going through withdrawal and experi-
encing craving (for example, by focusing predominantly on immediate 
relief from these negative affective states rather than on the long-term 
benefits of abstaining from opioid use). Negative urgency might also 
provide an integrative understanding of some emotion-elicited state 
impulsivity constructs120. A study in a mixed addiction sample found 
that increased negative urgency was a critical predictor of impair-
ments in ‘hot’ state impulsivity (such as delay discounting) across 
the addiction cycle, but had a minimal role in emotion-neutral state 
impulsivity (such as automatic response inhibition)178. Other studies 
found robust associations between negative urgency and deficits in 
response inhibition measured by tasks involving emotionally charged 
stimuli across normative and substance use disorder samples179–182.
Thus, negative urgency might be relevantly implicated in the 
withdrawal/negative affect stage of the opioid addiction cycle by ampli-
fying urges induced by intense negative emotions. Negative urgency is 
also implicated in the preoccupation/anticipation (craving) stage, by 
substantially challenging the capacity to control these urges even when 
not experiencing withdrawal symptomatology168. Through this lens, 
negative urgency seems to be among the critical trait-like mechanisms 
modulating impairments in emotion-elicited state impulsivity in opioid 
use disorder168. This mechanism is gaining increased recognition in the 
literature. Still, more research is needed to clarify its role in the opioid 
addiction cycle and the degree to which it operates as an antecedent 
risk factor versus a consequence of chronic opioid use.
Psychopathy
Psychopathy is a distinct personality disorder characterized by a spec-
trum of traits across affective (for example, lack of empathy and shallow 
affect), interpersonal (for example, grandiosity and manipulativeness), 
lifestyle (for example, impulsivity and irresponsibility) and antisocial 
(for example, aggressive and antisocial behaviour) dimensions183,184. 
Like other personality disorders, psychopathy typically develops early 
and is often lifelong. However, psychopathy has also been concep-
tualized as a dimensional personality trait with varying degrees of 
severity, rather than being classified strictly as a disorder185,186. This 
dimensional perspective implies that psychopathic traits can present 
in varying levels across individuals, regardless of clinical diagnosis. The 
complex constellation of unique features associated with prominent 
difficulties in impulse control and marked emotional disturbances183,184 
sets psychopathy apart from related conditions such as antisocial per-
sonality disorder and sociopathy, with which it is often confused but 
is not synonymous187,188. Psychopathy has been associated with risky 
and violent behaviours34,189–192, aggression193 and unfavourable treat-
ment outcomes194–196. People with opioid use disorder present with 
higher levels of psychopathy than neurotypical controls and stimulant 
users76,197, and psychopathy has been additionally associated with risky 
sexual behaviours in this group of patients34.
Traditional conceptualizations of psychopathy differentiate 
two latent structural dimensions: factor 1, associated with the affec-
tive and interpersonal characteristics of the disorder; and factor 2, 
reflecting impulsive and antisocial lifestyle and behaviours184. The 
two psychopathy factors have differential associations with negative 
emotionality198,199. Factor 1 predominantly indexes deficits in empathy, 
reduced capacity for guilt and remorse, and interpersonal features of 
the disorder. This factor encompasses traits associated with emotional 
detachment and does not indicate the absence of emotion. Indeed, indi-
viduals with psychopathy do not lack emotions (as proposed by early 
views of psychopathy200), but might often show a marked deficiency 
in the quality and range of their emotional experiences, particularly in 
contexts requiring empathy and remorse. Factor 1 is also associated 
with other forms of negative affectivity, such as proactive and reactive 
aggression201, hostility, and overall limited emotional awareness and 
emotion dysregulation202,203. These findings suggest marked difficul-
ties in emotion regulation and propensity to negative emotions203–205. 
By contrast, the impulsive and antisocial dimensions of psychopathy 
(factor 2) are closely related to negative emotions, such as anxiety206–208, 
alexithymia205,209,210 and negative urgency211–213.
Although psychopathy is recognized as a transdiagnostic marker 
of all substance use disorders76,95, machine-learning studies indicate 
Nature Reviews Psychology
Review article
that the affective and interpersonal dimension of psychopathy (factor 1) 
was the strongest and unique predictor of opioid dependence95,214, 
whereas factor 2 was associated with dependence on five different 
classes of drugs including opioids. Indeed, the unique combination of 
impulsive behaviour with negative affectivity in psychopathy seems to 
be among the key risk factors associated with vulnerability to opioid 
addiction. Similarly, opioid users show higher total psychopathy scores 
than other substance users76,95,197.
Opioids might be particularly appealing to individuals with 
high levels of psychopathy factor 1, who might use opioids for self-
medication to reduce distressing emotions associated with anger 
and hostility. Such anti-aggression and anti-rage action of opioids has 
already been noted as one of the most compelling reasons for their 
appeal215. Consistently, psychopathy fully mediated the link between 
opioid dependence and aggression in one study, whereas it only par-
tially mediated the link between alcohol or amphetamine dependence 
and aggression216. Additionally, psychopathy negatively impacts treat-
ment outcomes in opioid users217,218, supporting psychopathy’s role as 
a risk factor for failure to treat opioid use disorder.
Research suggests that psychopathy might intensify impairments in 
‘hot’ state impulsivity in opioid users, but remain unrelated to deficits 
in ‘cool’ state impulsivity219. In addition, studies suggest that the relative 
severity of the two psychopathy factors might be associated with either 
impaired or enhanced performance on tasks measuring emotion-driven 
and emotion-neutral state impulsivity in opioid users197. The interper-
sonal and affective dimension of psychopathy (factor 1) might have 
protective effects on both ‘hot’ decision-making and ‘cool’ response 
inhibition, whereas the impulsive and antisocial dimension (factor 2) 
might be related to poor performance on ‘cool’ impulsivity tasks197. 
However, these preliminary studies should be interpreted with caution 
until further replication, given that most of these findings are based on 
unique populations of abstinent and relatively mono-dependent heroin 
users in Bulgaria studied by our research group.
In sum, psychopathy is increasingly understood within a negative 
affectivity framework that focuses on the substantial involvement 
of negative affective states in the presentation and classification of 
the disorder, which has implications for understanding the opioid 
addiction cycle. First, psychopathy is a critical vulnerability marker for 
entering the addiction cycle. Individuals high in psychopathy were more 
prone to substance misuse via a negative emotionality pathway220 than 
via impulsivity-related mechanisms, as initially suggested221–223). How-
ever, impulsivity-related and negative emotionality pathways are not 
mutually exclusive and might account for distinct subtypes of substance 
users. Second, psychopathy might be particularly relevant in the later 
stages of the opioid addiction cycle, in which it might mitigate or exac-
erbate deficits in ‘hot’ and ‘cool’ impulsivity domains, posing challenges 
to treatment effectiveness. Given that emotion dysregulation has been 
proposed as a crucial underlying mechanism of psychopathy204 and a 
key mediator in the psychopathy–aggression nexus203,224, investigating 
the role of psychopathy in the associations between opioid use disorder 
and impulsivity is a vital line of enquiry for future studies.
Hyperkatifeia
Hyperkatifeia is a cluster of negative emotional and motivational symp-
toms stemming from drug withdrawal, centred on feelings of unease 
and dysphoria. It includes psychological symptoms such as irritability, 
anxiety, alexithymia and sleep problems, often contributing to a pro-
found sense of emotional discomfort and pain225. Repeated withdrawal 
episodes sensitize the brain stress and reward systems21 and lead to 
long-term neuroadaptations and neurochemical dysregulations, such 
as decreased dopamine and opioid peptide function, and increased 
corticotropin-releasing factor activity226. These neurobiological symp-
toms continue well into protracted abstinence, long after the acute 
withdrawal symptoms have subsided227.
Although primarily studied within the context of alcohol use 
disorder228, hyperkatifeia is also relevant to opioid use disorder. It is 
hypothesized to be a key part of the opioid addiction cycle and a key 
source of motivation for compulsive opioid use225,229. Hyperkatifeia 
is considered ‘the emotional corollary’ of hyperalgesia225,230, and the 
two have overlapping neural substrates, such as the central nucleus of 
the amygdala (the ‘nociceptive amygdala’231), which has an important 
role in emotional pain. Patients with opioid use disorder might be par-
ticularly attentive to opioid withdrawal-related cues that predict and 
elicit hyperkatifeia via conditioned withdrawal and motivate opioid 
seeking and use to alleviate hyperkatifeia via conditioned negative 
reinforcement227. As withdrawal symptoms intensify, cues become 
increasingly associated with these negative emotional states and 
acquire unique motivational properties that drive continued opioid use 
to avoid or reduce the negative emotional state of hyperkatifeia227. The 
aversive memories of the withdrawal-associated context can persist 
long after the period of acute withdrawal and further motivate opioid 
seeking and promote relapse227. This anticipatory fear of withdrawal 
symptoms and the desire to escape physical and emotional symp-
toms of withdrawal are key motivational factors that drive continued 
opioid use227. Of note, the emotional symptoms of hyperkatifeia might 
have higher motivational relevance than the somatic symptoms of 
withdrawal in the opioid addiction cycle225.
Trait and state dimensions of impulsivity could have a major role 
in moderating or mediating the effects of hyperkatifeia on perpetuat-
ing the cycle of opioid addiction. The negative emotional symptoms 
associated with hyperkatifeia might elicit intense urges for opioid 
use that are moderated or mediated in the withdrawal/negative affect 
stage by negative urgency168,232. In addition, impairments in ‘hot’ state 
impulsivity involving impulsive choice might further decrease exec-
utive control and the capacity to resist urges for opioid use in the 
preoccupation/anticipation stage168,232. Although the role of hyper-
katifeia as a key motivator driving the addiction cycle is increasingly 
recognized, more research is needed to elucidate its role in opioid and 
other types of addiction.
Pain and hyperalgesia
Opioids are recognized as the most effective drugs for the relief of acute 
pain, including negative emotional pain (although they are substantially 
less effective against chronic physical and emotional pain225). Unlike 
other addictive substances, opioids’ potent analgesic properties shape 
a unique pathway to opioid use disorder driven predominantly by the 
pursuit of pain relief, and opioid use disorder in many individuals has 
an iatrogenic origin. Indeed, the opioid epidemic in the United States 
was instigated by the widespread prescribing of opioids for pain relief 
under the false assumption that opioid medications were not addic-
tive. Early reviews of predominantly case series and cross-sectional 
studies in chronic pain samples suggested that as many as 25% or more 
of persons prescribed opioids for noncancer-pain developed opioid 
use disorder233.
For most substances of abuse, cohort studies long established that 
initiation of substance use typically starts with ‘softer’ drugs such as 
nicotine, alcohol or cannabis in individuals with behaviour problems in 
childhood, who gravitate towards other youths with deviant behaviour 
Nature Reviews Psychology
Review article
to derail normative academics and neurodevelopment, and embark 
on a trajectory that can culminate in crime or polysubstance use234. 
In a similar neurobiological framing, the ‘common liability hypothesis’ 
posits that the observed historical progression from ‘softer’ (cigarettes) 
to ‘harder’ (methamphetamine) drugs from young adolescence into 
adulthood stems from how an individual with a core latent neuro­
behavioural trait characterized by lack of self-control (impulsivity as 
the common liability) obtains access to harder drugs with increasing 
access to transportation and expanding social circles235. Put simply, 
non-opioid substance use disorders frequently stem from the ‘kind 
of person’ being initially exposed to drugs. By contrast, the role of 
individual temperament in developing opioid use disorder, although 
nevertheless present236, is probably lower relative to developing other 
substance use disorders. The progression towards dependence for a 
substantial portion of persons with opioid use disorder began with 
what was prescribed for pain. Even in persons with minimal psychiatric 
or temperamental risk factors, prescribed opioid use usually leads to 
tolerance owing to the neurochemical properties of the opioid system 
and, eventually, dependency.
Reviews of large-scale studies (predominantly electronic health 
records) conducted after the crackdown on opioid analgesic over-
prescribing reported a lower risk for persons prescribed opioids for 
pain to develop opioid use disorder (approximately 1% (ref. 237) to 
approximately 5% (refs. 238–240)). Differences across studies in esti-
mating precise rates might explain the different rates compared with 
the initial findings. For example, a meta-analysis indicated that rates 
of probable opioid use disorder in chronic pain (clinical) populations 
were higher (9–10%)241 than in the aforementioned electronic health 
records studies. Alternatively, these differences in rates might result 
from other differences in patient or clinic populations. A prior his-
tory of non-opioid substance use disorder236, affective disorders242 
or borderline personality disorder243 confers twofold or greater risk 
for developing iatrogenic opioid use disorder237,244,245 and affective 
disorders are overrepresented in chronic pain populations generally246. 
Overrepresentation of affective disorders can be attributed to how 
suffering from chronic pain can induce depression247, but reverse cau-
sality is also suggested: surgical patients with higher preoperative 
depression are characterized by greater subjective ratings of physical 
pain postoperatively248,249 and are more likely to request or otherwise 
receive opioids as their pain pharmacotherapy250,251.
In turn, chronic opioid use can result in hyperalgesia, an increased 
sensitivity to pain that involves the same brain stress systems implicated 
in hyperkatifeia225. This hyperalgesia, coupled with the rapid tolerance 
that opioid users develop for pain relief, typically drives pain patient 
requests for increasingly larger opioid doses, which are a risk factor for 
the development of opioid use disorder. Most Americans who reported 
use of diverted opioid medication in the past year were motivated 
primarily by pain relief rather than to feel good or to ‘get high’24.
In sum, two of the identified mechanisms (negative urgency and 
psychopathy) are traits that confer risk for opioid use disorder based 
on individual differences in impulsive personality characterized by 
negative emotionality. The two other mechanisms (hyperkatifeia 
and hyperalgesia) are states that reflect the progressively worsening 
effects of chronic opioid use on the negative affective symptoms of 
withdrawal and pain sensitivity (Box 3). The four mechanisms are 
substantiated by emerging evidence about unique motives for opioid 
use252, indicating that relative to alcohol, tobacco, cannabis, stimulants 
and tranquilizers, coping with withdrawal (including hyperkatifeia and 
hyperalgesia) is the primary motive for opioid use26. Along a spectrum 
of motivation for drug taking ranging from autopilot or compulsive 
behaviour to carefully planned instrumental behaviour, drug taking is 
considered more instrumental (goal orientated) than compulsive and 
automatized253. However, different substance use disorders might fall 
on different points on this spectrum8,25, and a fundamental distinction 
is that the use of opioids and the preoccupation with securing opioids is 
profoundly instrumentally driven for the explicit purpose of avoiding 
debilitatingly aversive withdrawal symptoms21. This motivation is typi-
cally not primary with other substances. This is one example of how 
diverse substance use disorders show distinct clinical presentations 
at the different stages of the addiction cycle (Fig. 2).
Summary and future directions
The increasing interest in negative reinforcement mechanisms and 
‘antireward’ brain systems is particularly relevant in opioid use disorder, 
Box 3 | Internalizing and externalizing 
personality domains
 
Individual differences in vulnerability to addiction have fostered 
calls for more customized or stratified interventions based on 
individual genetic propensities for stress proneness, impulsivity and 
other genetically influenced temperamental and neurobehavioural 
vulnerabilities341. This literature is most extensive for alcohol use 
disorder.
Decades of research on the personality and comorbidity 
factors of alcohol use disorder indicate a typology revealing two 
aetiological pathways to this disorder. Type A342/type 1 (ref. 343) 
alcohol use disorder is characterized by negative-affect-related 
drinking, and type B342/type 2343 is characterized by impulsive and 
antisocial behaviours. These typologies map onto an integrative 
conceptual framework in developmental psychology that 
posits two broad domains of personality and psychopathology: 
externalizing (impulsivity related) and internalizing (related 
to negative affect)344–347. These domains embody two distinct 
aetiological pathways to the development of substance use 
disorder, shown to be invariant across cultures, gender and age348.
Externalizing and internalizing typologies have been refined by 
modern personality-based approaches to substance use disorders, 
which reveal that specific externalizing and internalizing personality 
traits, characterized by unique neurocognitive, motivational 
and psychopathological profiles, are among the most salient 
vulnerability factors for drug addiction2,343,349. These personality traits 
have been differentially associated with vulnerability to different 
types of substance use disorders. For example, psychostimulant 
addiction is uniquely associated with externalizing traits such as 
impulsivity, whereas opioid addiction is more strongly related to 
internalizing traits such as anxiety sensitivity and hopelessness117,350.
Whereas earlier theories of personality considered impulsivity 
and negative affectivity (for example, neuroticism) as two separate 
pathways to addiction, these risk factors might be related. 
Internalizing aspects of negative affectivity associated with 
depression and anxiety have received extensive attention in the 
addiction literature; however, the role of externalizing aspects of 
negative affectivity associated with antisocial behaviours and traits 
have been understudied in the addiction literature and merit further 
investigation.
Nature Reviews Psychology
Review article
in which pain relief or emotional escape is the entry point into the addic-
tion cycle, and the salient negative emotional states trigger cravings 
and compulsive drug use21. These negative reinforcement mechanisms 
are essential pathways that drive impulsivity across all stages of opioid 
addiction and lead to a predominance of the withdrawal/negative affect 
stage21,29,254. During the binge/intoxication stage, ‘hot’ negative affec-
tive traits are antecedent risk factors that increase susceptibility to 
opioid addiction. During the preoccupation/anticipation stage, nega-
tive urgency and emotion-related choice impulsivity drive decisions 
whether to abstain or to use again. Finally, during the withdrawal/
negative affect stage, negative urgency and impulsive choice are 
prominent as opioid addiction is reinforced by withdrawal even after 
extended periods of abstinence.
Our framework seeks to consolidate current insights on impul-
sivity in opioid use disorder and offers a more nuanced perspective, 
weaving together the dynamic interplay between impulsivity and 
negative affect as defining elements of the cycle of opioid addiction. 
In this context, we identified four mechanisms by which ‘hot’ impul-
sivity might increase risk for opioid use disorder. Negative urgency 
and psychopathy are trait-like mechanisms with a bidirectional rela-
tionship with opioid use disorder: they are vulnerability factors for 
entering the opioid addiction cycle and shape the deficits in emotion-
elicited state impulsivity during the withdrawal/negative affect and 
preoccupation/anticipation stage. Complementary, hyperkatifeia 
and hyperalgesia are state-like mechanisms that can trigger a variety 
of impulsive choices and behaviours to provide at least momentary 
relief from the painful physical and emotional experiences of the 
withdrawal/negative affect stage.
Experienced treatment providers typically recognize the profound 
role of impulsivity in substance use disorders including opioid use 
disorder. This recognition is supported by decades of neurobehav-
ioural literature, but more often grows from patient testimonies and 
basic clinical observation. Indeed, cognitive behavioural therapies 
for substance use disorders typically focus on identifying triggers for 
use, and attempt to foster non-impulsive responses to life stressors 
(such as self-awareness of triggers and improved problem solving255,256). 
Targeting negative affect in opioid use disorder treatment in particu-
lar could improve the effectiveness of personality-targeted257,258 and 
neuroscience-informed259,260 prevention and intervention programmes. 
Psychoeducation content could focus heavily on the risks posed by 
negative emotional states and on increasing awareness of ‘hot’ impulsiv-
ity traits and states (such as negative urgency and decision-making) and 
their impact on substance use and other risk behaviours. In addition, 
broader lay knowledge of the deleterious role of negatively reinforced 
use of opioids in particular (to avoid withdrawal) could help expand 
medication-assisted treatment of opioid use disorder.
Future studies should address some of the gaps in knowledge 
and methodological limitations in the literature. Relative to other 
substance use disorders22–24, studies examining impulsivity dimen-
sions in opioid use disorder are few and far between16,25–27. Moreover, 
methodological limitations have hindered the acquisition of consistent 
knowledge. For example, most studies have either not controlled for 
comorbid substance use disorders or were conducted with hetero­
geneous samples of primarily polysubstance-dependent individu-
als, which complicates inferences about the specificity of findings to 
opioids. This problem is further compounded by the asymmetry of 
substance use disorders comorbidity; for example, more people with 
opioid use disorder meet criteria for alcohol use disorder (27.1%) than 
the reverse261, and by the time someone starts using opioids, they 
typically have been using other drugs28–30. Finally, most studies do not 
differentiate between the stages of the addiction cycle in participant 
recruitment, which introduces variability and poses additional chal-
