Fig. 2 | Motives and withdrawal effects across addictive substances. 
a, Stimulants (cocaine, amphetamine, methamphetamine, ecstasy and 
recreational alcohol) are used primarily for their euphoric properties (pink) 
and their use is typically positively reinforced well into the addiction process. 
Stimulant use motivation and acute drug effects map strongly onto the 
structures related to the binge/intoxication stage (blue) of the addiction cycle 
and the withdrawal and preoccupation stages are guided by reward prospects 
(orange). b, Opioids, sedatives and benzodiazepines are most frequently used 
for pain and negative emotion relief (green) and their use is primarily negatively 
reinforced. This motivation and the related drug effect feature a pronounced 
withdrawal/negative affect stage (olive green) and preoccupation/anticipation 
stage (grey).
Nature Reviews Psychology
Review article
impulsivity dimensions across the cycle of opioid addiction. Identifying 
the stage of the addiction cycle that participants were in at the time of 
testing across the studies included in our Review was not trivial; we 
mostly inferred this information based on grouping characteristics 
(such as active use versus abstinence or similar parameters).
The dynamic within-person changes in impulsivity associated with 
cycling through the different stages of addiction must be addressed 
using longitudinal ecological momentary assessment designs with 
self-report and neurocognitive measures of impulsivity. Future studies 
should also incorporate theory-driven and data-driven computational 
modelling approaches, which hold great promise for increasing the 
precision and reliability of measurement and the accuracy of progno-
sis and diagnosis in psychiatry75. These studies would then enable the 
development of targeted prevention and intervention programmes 
that focus on specific dimensions of impulsivity based on research 
domain criteria260.
Finally, a growing number of studies reveal that culture influ-
ences basic cognitive processes such as attention and perception262–264 
and higher cognitive functions and state impulsivity dimensions 
such as delay discounting265–267, decision-making268,269, cognitive 
flexibility270 and response inhibition271. However, these cultural 
aspects of emotion and cognition have been largely ignored in the 
addiction neuro­science literature. Interpreting present-centric pat-
terns of ­decision-making as ‘impulsive’ might not reflect the adaptive 
role of these tendencies in economically deprived or low-trust social 
structures in which future gains are uncertain at best272–274. Cultural dif-
ferences have also been observed in latent decision-making processes 
such as loss aversion275, a key parameter in computational models 
of decision-making. Notably, opioid users show a unique pattern of 
reduced sensitivity to loss76,276 that is also present in their unaffected 
siblings, which suggests this parameter’s potential endophenotypic 
importance. Despite acknowledging the necessity for cross-cultural 
validation of cognitive tasks and batteries, the vast majority of stud-
ies continue to be based on Western, educated, industrialized, rich 
and democratic277 samples that are typically outliers in cross-cultural 
comparisons278. Future studies should examine the mechanisms by 
which cross-cultural variability creates differences in the manifestation, 
interpretation and consequences of impulsivity in opioid use disorder 
and other substance use disorders via international interdisciplinary 
collaborations and consortia.
